{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RMQPxpUKJC7Rfcq57AxFQL","type":"tool_result","content":"70\t\n71\tThe canonical `doctor check-integrity` JSON report owns:\n72\t\n73\t- top-level keys: `physical`, `logical`, `semantic`\n74\t- per-finding fields: `code`, `stage`, `locator`, `doc_anchor`, `detail`\n75\t- single process exit code semantics for clean / findings / unrecoverable /\n76\t  lock-held outcomes\n77\t\n78\tThis design follows HITL `R9`; NDJSON is not the default `check-integrity`\n79\tcontract in 0.6.0.\n80\t\n81\t## JSON shapes for other doctor verbs\n82\t\n83\tEach non-`recover` machine-readable verb returns one JSON object with a stable\n84\t`verb` discriminator plus verb-owned keys.\n85\t\n86\t| Verb                     | Required top-level keys                                                                            | Notes                                                                             |\n87\t| ------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n88\t| `doctor safe-export`     | `verb`, `export_path`, `manifest_path`, `manifest_sha256`                                          | one object describing the completed export artifact and manifest                  |\n89\t| `doctor verify-embedder` | `verb`, `stored_identity`, `stored_dimension`, `supplied_identity`, `supplied_dimension`, `status` | `status` is a typed match/mismatch result, not free text                          |\n90\t| `doctor trace`           | `verb`, `source_ref`, `events`                                                                     | `events` is an ordered machine-readable lineage list for the requested source ref |\n91\t| `doctor dump-schema`     | `verb`, `user_version`, `tables`, `indexes`                                                        | schema inventory only; no recovery mutation                                       |\n92\t| `doctor dump-row-counts` | `verb`, `counts`                                                                                   | `counts` is an array of `{ name, rows }` records                                  |\n93\t| `doctor dump-profile`    | `verb`, `embedder_identity`, `embedder_dimension`, `vectorized_kinds`                              | stored profile / vector posture dump                                              |\n94\t\n95\t## Logical-id purge and restore\n96\t\n97\t`fathomdb recover --accept-data-loss --purge-logical-id <id>` and\n98\t`--restore-logical-id <id>` operate on the canonical identity model owned\n99\tby `design/engine.md § Canonical identity and supersession`. This section\n100\tspecifies their cascade scope, replay source, output report shape, and\n101\tfailure modes.\n102\t\n103\t### Cascade scope (`--purge-logical-id`)\n104\t\n105\tPurge is lossy. The cascade scope is:\n106\t\n107\t- **Canonical:** delete every physical row (`row_id`) matching the\n108\t  `logical_id`, across all canonical tables and kinds. Includes both\n109\t  active and superseded rows for that logical id.\n110\t- **`latest_state` op-store collections:** delete keyed entries for the\n111\t  logical id. `latest_state` is the current-state map and must not retain\n112\t  stale references.\n113\t- **Derived projections:** drop FTS rows and per-kind vector rows\n114\t  attributable to the logical id (the rows are no longer recoverable from\n115\t  canonical state).\n116\t- **`append_only_log` op-store collections:** **preserved**. The event\n117\t  stream is durable audit history and is the replay source for\n118\t  `--restore-logical-id`. Purge does not rewrite history.\n119\t- **Other sources:** untouched. Rows associated with sibling source ids\n120\t  remain. The non-perturbation rule from Pack B (`excise_source`) applies:\n121\t  no blanket projection rebuild; invalidate only the affected logical id.\n122\t\n123\tReport shape (`PurgeLogicalIdReport`):\n124\t\n125\t- `verb`\n126\t- `logical_id`\n127\t- `canonical_rows_deleted` — count, sum across kinds\n128\t- `latest_state_keys_deleted` — count\n129\t- `projection_rows_invalidated` — count, sum of FTS + vector rows\n130\t- `append_only_log_rows_preserved` — count, informational\n131\t- `status` — typed success / no-op (logical id not present) / partial\n132\t\n133\tFailure modes:\n134\t\n135\t- `LogicalIdNotFound` — id matches no canonical row and no `latest_state`\n136\t  key. Returns `status = no_op`, not a hard error.\n137\t- Standard transactional rollback on any sub-step failure; no partial\n138\t  purge state persists.\n139\t\n140\t### Replay source and semantics (`--restore-logical-id`)\n141\t\n142\tRestore replays the `append_only_log` write history for the logical id\n143\tback into canonical state through the standard writer:\n144\t\n145\t1. Read the ordered `append_only_log` events for the logical id.\n146\t2. Verify no active canonical row currently exists for the logical id\n147\t   (precondition for restore — restore does not overwrite live state).\n148\t3. Replay the event stream through the writer, producing canonical rows\n149\t   and supersession markers identical to the original write history,\n150\t   except the final active row carries a new `restore_provenance` field\n151\t   marking it as restoration output.\n152\t4. Re-derive projections (FTS + vector) from the restored active state.\n153\t5. Commit as one transaction.\n154\t\n155\tReport shape (`RestoreLogicalIdReport`):\n156\t\n157\t- `verb`\n158\t- `logical_id`\n159\t- `events_replayed` — count\n160\t- `canonical_rows_restored` — count, sum across kinds\n161\t- `projection_rows_rebuilt` — count\n162\t- `restore_cursor` — the `c_w` of the commit\n163\t- `status` — typed success / failure variant\n164\t\n165\tFailure modes (typed; not free-text):\n166\t\n167\t- `NoRestorationSource` — `append_only_log` has no events for the logical\n168\t  id. Restore is impossible.\n169\t- `ConflictingActiveRow` — a canonical row with `superseded_at IS NULL`\n170\t  already exists for the logical id. Operator must purge first or accept\n171\t  the existing row.\n172\t- `IncompatibleSchema` — replay would write columns or kinds no longer\n173\t  present in the current schema. Restore aborts; the operator must\n174\t  migrate manually.\n175\t- Standard transactional rollback on writer / projection failures.\n176\t\n177\tRestore is reachable only via `recover --accept-data-loss\n178\t--restore-logical-id <id>`; it is not an SDK runtime verb, consistent\n179\twith the `recover` boundary in `ADR-0.6.0-cli-scope`.\n180\t\n181\t## `recover` machine-readable output\n182\t\n183\t`recover --json` is the only NDJSON-style machine-readable surface in 0.6.0.\n184\t\n185\tProgress records carry:\n186\t\n187\t- `action`\n188\t- `status`\n189\t- `detail`"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6045b345-74e5-4485-9471-2a1561990851","uuid":"8c679369-fe5e-4293-baf3-2e375e05ee23","timestamp":"2026-05-15T23:41:58.376Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-10b-A-low-risk-seams-20260515T234104Z/dev/design/recovery.md","content":"\nThe canonical `doctor check-integrity` JSON report owns:\n\n- top-level keys: `physical`, `logical`, `semantic`\n- per-finding fields: `code`, `stage`, `locator`, `doc_anchor`, `detail`\n- single process exit code semantics for clean / findings / unrecoverable /\n  lock-held outcomes\n\nThis design follows HITL `R9`; NDJSON is not the default `check-integrity`\ncontract in 0.6.0.\n\n## JSON shapes for other doctor verbs\n\nEach non-`recover` machine-readable verb returns one JSON object with a stable\n`verb` discriminator plus verb-owned keys.\n\n| Verb                     | Required top-level keys                                                                            | Notes                                                                             |\n| ------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| `doctor safe-export`     | `verb`, `export_path`, `manifest_path`, `manifest_sha256`                                          | one object describing the completed export artifact and manifest                  |\n| `doctor verify-embedder` | `verb`, `stored_identity`, `stored_dimension`, `supplied_identity`, `supplied_dimension`, `status` | `status` is a typed match/mismatch result, not free text                          |\n| `doctor trace`           | `verb`, `source_ref`, `events`                                                                     | `events` is an ordered machine-readable lineage list for the requested source ref |\n| `doctor dump-schema`     | `verb`, `user_version`, `tables`, `indexes`                                                        | schema inventory only; no recovery mutation                                       |\n| `doctor dump-row-counts` | `verb`, `counts`                                                                                   | `counts` is an array of `{ name, rows }` records                                  |\n| `doctor dump-profile`    | `verb`, `embedder_identity`, `embedder_dimension`, `vectorized_kinds`                              | stored profile / vector posture dump                                              |\n\n## Logical-id purge and restore\n\n`fathomdb recover --accept-data-loss --purge-logical-id <id>` and\n`--restore-logical-id <id>` operate on the canonical identity model owned\nby `design/engine.md § Canonical identity and supersession`. This section\nspecifies their cascade scope, replay source, output report shape, and\nfailure modes.\n\n### Cascade scope (`--purge-logical-id`)\n\nPurge is lossy. The cascade scope is:\n\n- **Canonical:** delete every physical row (`row_id`) matching the\n  `logical_id`, across all canonical tables and kinds. Includes both\n  active and superseded rows for that logical id.\n- **`latest_state` op-store collections:** delete keyed entries for the\n  logical id. `latest_state` is the current-state map and must not retain\n  stale references.\n- **Derived projections:** drop FTS rows and per-kind vector rows\n  attributable to the logical id (the rows are no longer recoverable from\n  canonical state).\n- **`append_only_log` op-store collections:** **preserved**. The event\n  stream is durable audit history and is the replay source for\n  `--restore-logical-id`. Purge does not rewrite history.\n- **Other sources:** untouched. Rows associated with sibling source ids\n  remain. The non-perturbation rule from Pack B (`excise_source`) applies:\n  no blanket projection rebuild; invalidate only the affected logical id.\n\nReport shape (`PurgeLogicalIdReport`):\n\n- `verb`\n- `logical_id`\n- `canonical_rows_deleted` — count, sum across kinds\n- `latest_state_keys_deleted` — count\n- `projection_rows_invalidated` — count, sum of FTS + vector rows\n- `append_only_log_rows_preserved` — count, informational\n- `status` — typed success / no-op (logical id not present) / partial\n\nFailure modes:\n\n- `LogicalIdNotFound` — id matches no canonical row and no `latest_state`\n  key. Returns `status = no_op`, not a hard error.\n- Standard transactional rollback on any sub-step failure; no partial\n  purge state persists.\n\n### Replay source and semantics (`--restore-logical-id`)\n\nRestore replays the `append_only_log` write history for the logical id\nback into canonical state through the standard writer:\n\n1. Read the ordered `append_only_log` events for the logical id.\n2. Verify no active canonical row currently exists for the logical id\n   (precondition for restore — restore does not overwrite live state).\n3. Replay the event stream through the writer, producing canonical rows\n   and supersession markers identical to the original write history,\n   except the final active row carries a new `restore_provenance` field\n   marking it as restoration output.\n4. Re-derive projections (FTS + vector) from the restored active state.\n5. Commit as one transaction.\n\nReport shape (`RestoreLogicalIdReport`):\n\n- `verb`\n- `logical_id`\n- `events_replayed` — count\n- `canonical_rows_restored` — count, sum across kinds\n- `projection_rows_rebuilt` — count\n- `restore_cursor` — the `c_w` of the commit\n- `status` — typed success / failure variant\n\nFailure modes (typed; not free-text):\n\n- `NoRestorationSource` — `append_only_log` has no events for the logical\n  id. Restore is impossible.\n- `ConflictingActiveRow` — a canonical row with `superseded_at IS NULL`\n  already exists for the logical id. Operator must purge first or accept\n  the existing row.\n- `IncompatibleSchema` — replay would write columns or kinds no longer\n  present in the current schema. Restore aborts; the operator must\n  migrate manually.\n- Standard transactional rollback on writer / projection failures.\n\nRestore is reachable only via `recover --accept-data-loss\n--restore-logical-id <id>`; it is not an SDK runtime verb, consistent\nwith the `recover` boundary in `ADR-0.6.0-cli-scope`.\n\n## `recover` machine-readable output\n\n`recover --json` is the only NDJSON-style machine-readable surface in 0.6.0.\n\nProgress records carry:\n\n- `action`\n- `status`\n- `detail`","numLines":120,"startLine":70,"totalLines":320}}}
